article.description: It took Peja Stojakovic, Doug Christie and the Sacramento Kings about three minutes to get going.  Then the Seattle SuperSonics got in serious trouble.

related.description: Bobby Jackson might not be cosmetically healthy, but he's ready to return from a seven-week stint on the injured list. He was activated by the Sacramento Kings on Friday after missing 21 games with a broken left hand.
related.linkText: Jackson returns to Kings after seven weeks on IL
related.title: Jackson's hand scarred, but he's happy to be back

article.headline: Kings enjoy near-perfect night, Sonics' woes deepen
article.linkText: Kings can do no wrong in 29-point rout of Sonics
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- There are a few games every season in which Doug Christie simply knows his behind-the-back passes will always find their target, when Peja Stojakovic knows his most difficult jumpers will find the net.
 
Clark
 
Stojakovic
The Sacramento Kings' 110-81 victory over the Seattle SuperSonics on Friday night was one of those games -- when the hardened, playoff-tested Kings look like the carefree run-and-gunners who started their run to a spot among the NBA's elite five years ago with performances just like this. Keon Clark had 18 points, a season-high 14 rebounds and six blocked shots, and Stojakovic scored 24 points as the Kings shot 67 percent in the first three quarters. Christie matched his career high with 13 assists, and Mike Bibby had 18 points on 8-of-9 shooting as the Pacific Division leaders got back into top form. "Offensively, this was one of those nights when it was just flowing,'' Christie said. "We really came out and executed well. Our defense was really good, too. It was just solid on both ends. We looked good.'' Eight Kings scored at least eight points, and Sacramento threatened the franchise record of 65.4 percent shooting set two years ago before a mediocre fourth quarter by the reserves. Led by Christie's nine assists, the Kings took a 22-point lead in the first quarter. Stojakovic highlighted an 18-4 run with consecutive 3-pointers in the third quarter as Sacramento earned its second blowout win over Seattle in 15 days. "It was such a solid game,'' Kings coach Rick Adelman said. "What I liked about it was that we came out at the start of the game and we jumped on them, and then came out in the third quarter and jumped on them again. It was a good sign.'' Gary Payton had 20 points and Rashard Lewis shook off a sprained ankle to score 11, but Seattle never challenged in its fifth straight loss. The Sonics have fallen to 11th place in the Western Conference. "We can't continue to keep getting beat the way we're getting beat,'' said Desmond Mason, who scored 12 points. "We're not even close. It got out of hand quick. It seems like we can't get anything going at either end of the floor, no matter who starts or who comes off the bench.'' Bobby Jackson, activated from the injured list earlier in the day, scored eight points. Stojakovic hit four 3-pointers, and Clark played 40 dominant minutes as the starting power forward in Chris Webber's absence. After losing five of seven before the All-Star break, the Kings have recovered with victories in the first two games of a seven-game homestand. It continues on Sunday against San Antonio, which handed Sacramento its first home loss of the season in December. Jackson was back after missing 21 games with a broken left hand, but his instant offense wasn't needed. Wearing a protective wrap, Jackson got a standing ovation late in the first quarter when he entered his first game since Dec. 25. "I still need to get my rhythm,'' said Jackson, who played 17 minutes. "I was a little lost out there, but I'm glad the guys got off to a good start so it took a lot of pressure off of me.'' The Kings took the reeling Sonics out of the game with a dominant first quarter. With Christie distributing the ball with his usual flair, Sacramento led 21-7 after six minutes _ making 11 straight shots at one point _ and 34-12 at the end of the quarter. "We just didn't make any shots tonight,'' Payton said. "Everybody is going to have to buckle down and learn how to play the game, and right now, we're not playing the game well. We're not playing the way we're supposed to play, and teams are exploiting us.'' With nine assists in the first quarter, Christie fell one short of the franchise record set by Kenny Smith on Feb. 11, 1988. Sacramento shot better than 70 percent until the final minutes of the first half, and the Kings laughed and joked among themselves throughout the second half.

Game notes
Kings F Gerald Wallace was a last-minute scratch with a bruised right quadriceps, so Clark stepped into the starting lineup. Sacramento is 5-2 when Clark starts. ... The Sonics activated Vladimir Radmanovic and put Kenny Anderson on the injured list with back spasms. Anderson has been bothered by the injury for nearly a week. Radmanovic had five points. ... Sacramento won 95-77 at Seattle on Jan. 30. ... Stojakovic, who slumped for nearly three months this season, has scored at least 20 points in six straight games. ... Seattle has scored 100 points just twice in the last 25 games.
